The '''Hogwarts Express''' is a train that carries students non-stop from [[Platform 9¾|Platform {{frac|9|3|4}}]] at [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross station]] in London to [[Hogsmeade]] Station, near Hogwarts. Prefects of the school ride in a separate carriage near the front of the train. The compartments on the train appear to be lettered; in ''Half-Blood Prince'', the &quot;Slug Club&quot; meets in compartment C.

The train began use in the 1850s. Before that, students used to reach Hogwarts on brooms or enchanted carriages.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last1=Rowling|first1=J. K.|title=The Hogwarts Express|url=https://www.pottermore.com/writing-by-jk-rowling/the-hogwarts-express|website=Pottermore|accessdate=3 September 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The steam engine used in the film adaptations is the [[GWR 4900 Class 5972 Olton Hall|GWR 4900 Class 5972 ''Olton Hall'']], but it was not the first locomotive to be disguised as the Hogwarts Express. To promote the books, the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]] locomotive ''[[SR West Country class 21C127 Taw Valley|34027 Taw Valley]]'' was repainted and renamed temporarily, but was rejected by director [[Chris Columbus (filmmaker)|Chris Columbus]] as looking 'too modern' for the film. Filming locations for the Hogwarts Express sequences include [[Goathland railway station|Goathland]] on the [[North Yorkshire Moors Railway]], [[London King's Cross railway station|Kings Cross railway station]] and the route of the Jacobite Express which follows the [[West Highland Line]] from [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]] to [[Mallaig railway station|Mallaig]] in Scotland, as it crosses the [[Glenfinnan Viaduct]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.steamtrain.info/harry.htm|title=Harry Potter Express|publisher=steamtrain.info|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080813211628/http://www.steamtrain.info/harry.htm|archivedate=13 August 2008|accessdate=2 September 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Several model trains have been made of the Hogwarts Express. An [[00 gauge]] is produced by [[Hornby Railways|Hornby]], though this is of a [[GWR 4073 Class|Castle Class]] locomotive rather than the [[GWR 4900 Class|Hall Class]] used in the films. A [[third rail|three-rail]] [[H0 gauge]] model is produced by [[Märklin]], and a two-rail H0/00 was produced in the early 2000s by [[Bachmann Industries|Bachmann]]. Several now-discontinued [[L gauge]] models have been produced by [[Lego Group|LEGO]]. [[Lionel Corp.|Lionel]] has released an [[O scale|O gauge]] set in their 2007 catalogue and a [[G scale|G gauge]] set for 2008.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Harry PotterTM HogwartsTM Express O-Gauge (4-6-0 Conv. LOCO #5972)|url=http://www.lionel.com/products/harry-pottertm-hogwartstm-express-o-gauge-4-6-0-conv-loco-5972-7-11020/|publisher=Lionel|accessdate=3 February 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Harry Potter Hogwarts Express G-Gauge Passenger Set (LOCO #5972)|url=http://www.lionel.com/products/harry-potter-hogwarts-express-g-gauge-passenger-set-loco-5972-7-11080/|publisher=Lionel|accessdate=3 February 2016}}&lt;/ref&gt;

A completely functioning [[Hogwarts Express (Universal Orlando Resort)|full-scale replica of the Hogwarts Express]] was created for [[The Wizarding World of Harry Potter (Universal Orlando Resort)|The Wizarding World of Harry Potter]]'s expansion at [[Universal Orlando Resort]] connecting King's Cross Station at the Diagon Alley expansion in [[Universal Studios Florida]] to the Hogsmeade station at [[Islands of Adventure]],&lt;ref name=&quot;What may come to Wizarding World of Harry Potter 2.0 at Universal Orlando&quot;&gt;{{cite news|last=MacDonald|first=Brady|title=What may come to Wizarding World of Harry Potter 2.0 at Universal Orlando|url=http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-diagon-alley-wizarding-world-harry-potter-universal-studios-05201309,0,640470,full.story|accessdate=18 May 2013|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=9 May 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130510183411/http://www.latimes.com/travel/deals/themeparks/la-trb-diagon-alley-wizarding-world-harry-potter-universal-studios-05201309%2C0%2C640470%2Cfull.story|archivedate=10 May 2013}}&lt;/ref&gt; manufactured by [[Doppelmayr Garaventa Group]] in the form of a [[funicular]] railway [[people mover]].&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite press release|title=Doppelmayr/Garaventa built the Hogwarts Express|url=http://newsroom.doppelmayr.com/en/doppelmayr/news/doppelmayr-garaventa-built-the-hogwarts-express/|accessdate=6 September 2014|date=25 July 2014|publisher=Doppelmayr Garaventa Group}}&lt;/ref&gt; The Hogwarts Express King's Cross Station features a wall between Platforms 9 and 10, where guests can &quot;walk through&quot; to get to Platform {{frac|9|3|4}}, as in the first film.

