==In translation==
{{unreferenced-section|date=December 2019}}
Most translations keep the name 'Hogwarts', [[transcription (linguistics)|transcribing]] it if necessary (for example Arabic {{lang|ar|هوغوورتس}} = ''Hūghwūrts'', Russian {{lang|ru|Хогвартс}} = ''Khogvarts'', Japanese {{lang|ja|ホグワーツ}} = ''Hoguwātsu'', Bengali {{lang|bn|হগওয়ার্টস}} = ''Hogowarts'', [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|el|Χόγκουαρτς}} = ''Hóguarts'', simplified Chinese {{lang|zh-cn|霍格沃茨}} = ''Huògéwòcí''). But some translate or otherwise adapt it: French ''{{lang|fr|Poudlard}}'' (''{{lang|fr|lard}}'' = &quot;[[bacon]]&quot;), [[Latvian language|Latvian]] ''{{lang|lv|Cūkkārpas}}'' shortened from ''{{lang|lv|cūka}}'' = &quot;pig&quot; + ''{{lang|lv|kārpas}}'' = &quot;[[wart]]s&quot;, Dutch ''{{lang|nl|Zweinstein}}'' modified from ''{{lang|nl|zwijnsteen}}'' = &quot;pig rock&quot; while simultaneously referencing [[Albert Einstein]], Norwegian [[Bokmål]] ''{{lang|nb|Galtvort}}'' (galt = boar, vort = wart) ([[Nynorsk]] keeps &quot;{{lang|nn|Hogwarts}}&quot;), [[Finnish language|Finnish]] ''{{lang|fi|Tylypahka}}'' (''{{lang|fi|pahka}}'' = &quot;[[wart]]&quot;), Hungarian ''{{lang|hu|Roxfort}}'' (playing with the name of [[Oxford]]), [[Slovene language|Slovenian]] ''{{lang|sl|Bradavičarka}}'' (''{{lang|sl|bradavice}}'' = &quot;warts&quot;)), [[Czech language|Czech]] ''{{lang|cs|Bradavice}}'' means simply &quot;[[wart]]s&quot;. The [[Ancient Greek language|Ancient Greek]] translation of the school is &quot;Ὑογοήτου Παιδευτήριον τὸ τῆς Γοητείας καὶ Μαγείας&quot;, loosely translating to &quot;Hogwizard's School of Wizardry and Magic&quot;, ''Ὑογοήτου'' replacing &quot;Hogwarts&quot; and derived from the ancient Greek words ὑo- (hog) and γοητής (wizard).

